 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'oleavr', 'comment_id': 639865935.0, 'datetime': '2020-06-05 22:24:55+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_1', 'text': 'Our existing bridges take advantage of JavaScript's being a dynamic language. That means we can use [Proxy](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Proxy) objects to lazily generate language bindings on-the-fly without having to do any work up front. It also means you can do `obj.Foo()` without any code generation step as you would need when using C++. The bridge will get a callback where it's looking up `Foo`, and can then go ahead and call into the runtime to find that particular method/field. It accomplishes this using `NativeFunction` and other low-level primitives that Frida's JavaScript APIs expose.

But to the user it's really simple:

```js
Java.perform(() => {
  const Activity = Java.use('android.app.Activity');

  // Allowing you to call static methods on the Activity class:
  Activity.foo();

  // One can also call instance methods, but that requires getting hold of an instance first,
  // which can be accomplished using Java.choose().

  // And you can replace a method implementation:
  Activity.onResume.implementation = function () {
    console.log("onResume() got called! Let's call the original implementation");
    this.onResume();
  };
});
```', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'manishsahani999', 'comment_id': 640462682.0, 'datetime': '2020-06-08 08:47:54+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_0', 'text': 'Hey @username_1, thanks for the explanation, I understood the part of lazily generate bindings on-the-fly without having any work to do, and how we can make use of NativeFuntion to make a call to `Obj.Foo()`, this all looks good and I agree on this, but I have a small doubt here that for calling this the `NativeFunction` we have to pass `address` as the first argument, how do find the address of the `Obj.Foo` function? 

let start from a really simple program, that prints a string after every 2 secs.
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <windows.h>

void hello() {
    std::cout << "Hello Frida!\n";
}

int main() {
    printf("The fun address is %p\n", hello);
    while (true)
    {
        hello();
        Sleep(2000);
    }
    return 0;
}
```
we can hook the function if we have the address, but these are not present in `DebugSymbol` (In your NDC talk you mentioned this for a bit, these are not exported or something?), and we can't get the address of this function/variables. then how the `NativeFunction` will be called? 

manually I can get the base address and add the offset or from the `printf("The fun address is %p\n", hello);` I can directly use, Can you tell how this can be achived inorder to use `NativeFunciton`.', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'oleavr', 'comment_id': 640556168.0, 'datetime': '2020-06-08 11:52:44+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_1', 'text': '@username_0 That is what the .NET runtime (VM) knows and the bridge is in charge of querying it so it can instantiate a `NativeFunction` with the correct address and signature.', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'manishsahani999', 'comment_id': 646356766.0, 'datetime': '2020-06-18 23:35:50+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_0', 'text': 'Hey @username_1, 

So far I have written some hacky code just to get more comfortable with the notion of the bridge, I am able to do querying for the functions but when I am invoking them, getting a memory access error,  `Error: access violation accessing 0x6c6c6568`,  

I am enumerating over exports and registering them so that a user can do something like create a new instance and in this direction 
```js 
var query = QueryModule.find(Classname)
```
and user can use this query to do stuff like 
```js
// to create a new object 
var queryObj = query.create(...args_list);

// to get properties  
console.log(queryObj.some_property);

// to replace the implementation of a method
query.method.replace = () {
    cosole.log("replace with new")
}
```
The idea here is to attach a DLL which has helper functions for using STL, like updating a string, reading a std::string etc. and a js Module to project these C++ functions into js.

To reproduce, the small DLL has a function, and js module finds function 
```c
// update string 
extern "C" void updateStr(std::string & src, const char* target_val) {
     src = target;
}
```

```js
var strptr = Module.findExportByName('CppBridge.dll', 'updateStr');

var update_str = new NativeFunction(strptr, 'void', ['pointer', 'pointer']);
send("loaded");

var str1 = Memory.allocUtf8String("hello");
var str2 = Memory.allocUtf8String("world");
send(str1)
send(str2)

var r = update_str(str1, str2);
send(r)
send("string 1 = " + str1);
send("string 2 = " + str2);
```

`Error: access violation accessing 0x6c6c6568`, comes at the function calling line

can you tell me how can I solve this memory?', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}]

[{'action': 'opened', 'author': 'jbergstroem', 'comment_id': None, 'datetime': '2016-05-03 04:21:44+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_0', 'text': "Since we're using `gzip_static on` in the server we could shave off an considerable amount of cpu power by storing a gzip representation of each file we deploy (for instance `index.html` would be accompanied by `index.html.gz`). Additionally, since we default to `-6` in nginx, we'd likely make each file a bit smaller by using `-9` on deploy.", 'title': 'Store gzip representations of common files on deploy', 'type': 'issue'}
